<subSubSection id="C31AF6E6FFEDFFC0B487FCF2FC514623" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BBFA56DFFEDFFC0B487FCF2FDCA40AF" blockId="11.[151,1437,762,1941]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B487FCF2FEE94073" bold="true" box="[199,334,835,861]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named for the village of Kuyamu, a community of Barbareño Chumash that once stood onshore at the site where the sponge was discovered.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBFA56DFFEDFFC0B487FC3AFB1B473F" blockId="11.[151,1437,762,1941]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B487FC3AFEC6408B" bold="true" box="[199,353,907,933]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">Morphology.</emphasis>
Encrusting, 
<quantity id="4CF80888FFEDFFC0B5B1FC3AFDE9408B" box="[497,590,907,933]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" unit="mm" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2 mm</quantity>
thick, 
<quantity id="4CF80888FFEDFFC0B6DDFC3AFD72408B" box="[669,725,907,933]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" unit="cm" value="6.0">6 cm</quantity>
across (
<figureCitation id="133BB9E8FFEDFFC0B773FC3AFCDE408B" box="[819,889,907,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="12.[151,250,943,967]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,920]" captionTargetId="figure-23@12.[151,1436,181,920]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scopalina kuyamu sp. nov.. All images from holotype.A: field photo. B: Skeletal architecture, showing basal plate cored with copious sediment. C, D spicules." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4761877" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4761877/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Soft and compressible. Surface hispid due to a profusion of protruding styles. Distinct ectosome not apparent. Peach colored in nature, except for translucent-white varicose channels running along surface. Few scattered oscules, each ~300 μm diameter; smaller pores (approxi- mately 80 μm diameter) abundant and uniformly distributed. Beige when preserved in ethanol.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBFA56DFFEDFFC0B487FBABFD95478F" blockId="11.[151,1437,762,1941]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B487FBABFE92471A" bold="true" box="[199,309,1050,1076]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">Skeleton.</emphasis>
Basal mat of spongin cored with sediment. Extensions of spongin arise from this mat: most are low mounds, some only 25–50 μm high, but some are fingers 100–300 μm high and cored with sediment. Heads of spic- ules are embedded in these mounds and fingers, either singly or in bundles of up to 12. Spicules extent vertically and pierce the surface of the sponge.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBFA56DFFEDFFC0B487FB1BFC514623" blockId="11.[151,1437,762,1941]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B487FB1BFE9747EA" bold="true" box="[199,304,1194,1220]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">Spicules.</emphasis>
Styles only, usually bent towards the head end, thickest at the head and tapered to a point. Some spicule tips are “telescoping” (width decreasing in a step-wise fashion) at the pointed end. Spicules averaged 1557 μm in length (N=35, range 879–1948 μm); 16 μm in width (N=35, range 11–21).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31AF6E6FFEDFFC0B487FAA7FF5A46EF" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BBFA56DFFEDFFC0B487FAA7FF5A46EF" blockId="11.[151,1437,762,1941]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B487FAA7FE56461E" bold="true" box="[199,497,1302,1329]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
Only a single individual has been found, on a vertical wall at 
<quantity id="4CF80888FFEDFFC0B0E7FAA6FB47461F" box="[1191,1248,1303,1329]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" unit="m" value="12.0">12 m</quantity>
depth, at Naples Reef, in Santa Barbara, 
<collectingRegion id="49C46B8FFFEDFFC0B5E6FA8AFDBC467B" box="[422,539,1339,1365]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">California</collectingRegion>
. Habitat was rocky reef with abundant bryozoan, sponge, and anthozoan cover, adjacent to year-round kelp forest. Three additional dives at the same location failed to locate other individuals; similar, nearby habitat to the East and West also had considerable search effort, so this species appears to be rare in this area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31AF6E6FFEDFFC0B487FA7AFCF644BB" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BBFA56DFFEDFFC0B487FA7AFB844593" blockId="11.[151,1437,762,1941]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B487FA7AFE9C46CB" bold="true" box="[199,315,1483,1509]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">Remarks.</emphasis>
This sponge is quite genetically and morphologically distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="4C00DEEEFFEDFFC0B018FA7AFB7B46CA" authorityName="Turner" authorityYear="2021" box="[1112,1244,1483,1509]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="nausicae">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B018FA7AFB7B46CA" box="[1112,1244,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">S. nausicae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C00DEEEFFEDFFC0B15AFA7AFAF846CB" authorityName="Turner" authorityYear="2021" box="[1306,1375,1483,1509]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="jali">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B15AFA7AFAF846CB" box="[1306,1375,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">S. jali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The spicular architecture is fairly similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C00DEEEFFEDFFC0B60DFA5EFD7E4527" authorityName="Turner" authorityYear="2021" box="[589,729,1519,1545]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="goletensis">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B60DFA5EFD7E4527" box="[589,729,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">S. goletensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, though the spicule density is lower. As a result, 
<taxonomicName id="4C00DEEEFFEDFFC0B0B8FA5EFA244527" authorityName="Turner" authorityYear="2021" box="[1272,1411,1519,1545]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="goletensis">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B0B8FA5EFA244527" box="[1272,1411,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">S. goletensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is removable from the substrate as a fairly firm sheet, while 
<taxonomicName id="4C00DEEEFFEDFFC0B761F9A2FC334503" authorityName="Turner" authorityYear="2021" box="[801,916,1555,1581]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="kuyamu">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B761F9A2FC334503" box="[801,916,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">S. kuyamu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
peels away in rubbery strips that curl up upon themselves. Also, the spicules average over twice as long in 
<taxonomicName id="4C00DEEEFFEDFFC0B70BF986FC18457F" authorityName="Turner" authorityYear="2021" box="[843,959,1591,1617]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="kuyamu">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B70BF986FC18457F" box="[843,959,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">S. kuyamu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with non-overlapping size ranges among the spicules measured. These morphological differences seem unlikely to be due to environmental influences, as the two species were collected at the same depth, at very similar reefs, less than 
<quantity id="4CF80888FFEDFFC0B7A7F9CFFBB845B7" box="[999,1055,1662,1689]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" unit="km" value="5.0">5 km</quantity>
apart. Together with the considerable genetic divergence, these differences support species status for both species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBFA56DFFEDFFC0B487F976FBD14463" blockId="11.[151,1437,762,1941]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">
Among 
<taxonomicName id="4C00DEEEFFEDFFC0B563F976FE3445CF" authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1862" box="[291,403,1735,1761]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B563F976FE3445CF" box="[291,403,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">Scopalina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other regions, the only species with spicules as large as 
<taxonomicName id="4C00DEEEFFEDFFC0B00DF976FB6745CF" authorityName="Turner" authorityYear="2021" box="[1101,1216,1735,1761]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="kuyamu">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B00DF976FB6745CF" box="[1101,1216,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">S. kuyamu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are 
<taxonomicName id="4C00DEEEFFEDFFC0B0B2F976FDF8442B" authority="(Schmidt, 1862) (Blanquer &amp; Uriz 2008)" authorityName="Blanquer &amp; Uriz" authorityYear="2008" baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1862" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lophyropoda">
<emphasis id="B974797FFFEDFFC0B0B2F976FA3B45CF" box="[1266,1436,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="364">S. lophyropoda</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF91D89CFFEDFFC0B4DFF95AFEE34428" author="Schmidt, O." box="[159,324,1771,1798]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" refId="ref11625" refString="Schmidt, O. (1862) Die Spongien des adriatischen Meeres. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig, 88 pp." type="book" year="1862">Schmidt, 1862</bibRefCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="EF91D89CFFEDFFC0B51AF95AFDFF442B" author="Blanquer, A. &amp; Uriz, M. - J." box="[346,600,1771,1797]" pageId="11" pageNumber="364" pagination="489 - 502" refId="ref9181" refString="Blanquer, A. &amp; Uriz, M. - J. (2008) &quot; A posteriori &quot; searching for phenotypic characters to described new cryptic species of sponges revealed by molecular markers (Scopalina: Dictyonellidae). Invertebrate Systematics, 22, 489 - 502. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / IS 07004" type="journal article" year="2008">Blanquer &amp; Uriz 2008</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(Mediterranean) and 
